Pharmacy students tour

By Julie Holaren
For The Pitt News

A large group of Pitt phar-
macy students learned about
controversial health-care and
animal research topics dur-
ing a recent recruitment tour
of pharmaceutical company
Eli Lilly.

Instead of parties and
relaxing in the Florida sun
over Spring Break, the 80
students saw the
Indianapolis company’s
research laboratories, drug
packaging assembly line and
technology centers that pro-
duce drug insulin and
xarious capsules and tab-
lets.

Company officials
addressed the skyrocketing
prices of drugs, a controver-
health-care topic.
Fourth-year student Jeffrey
Smith said there are miscon-
eeptions about the high
prices. I

"A majority of the public
doesn’t understand that it



costs about $525 million to
get one drug on the market,”
Smith said.

Mary Jo Carden, another
pharmacy student, said that
patients often do not under-
stand that their insurance
deductibles do not always
cover pharmaceutical prod-
ucts used during hospital
stays.

Animal testing, another
issue facing the pharmaceuti-
cal industry today, was
addressed during a tour of
the toxicology department,
where animal experiments
take place.

Company officials said
they do not abuse the ani-
mals but did not allow the
students‘ to see many ani-
mals, saying that ‘distractions
could ruin the testing proce-
dure.

Eli Lilly stressed that,
unlike many other pharma-
ceutical industries, a majority
of the company’s sales repre-
sentatives are actual pharma-
cists. In fact, presently all

CEOs of the company are
pharmacists.

“I think they value pharma-
cists more than other phar-
maceutical companies
because of our chemistry
training, knowledge of how
drugs work and patient
counseling,” Carden said.
“Another reason may be that
Eli Lilly, himself, was a phar-
macist.”

Eli Lilly’s Cray supercom-
puter, one of few in the
country, interested many stu-
dents. The computer has the
power to rearrange mole-
cules to fit different hu-
man biological receptors
to make new drugs or
check the efficiency of old
drugs. “

Students said that this type
of computer research is the
fastest-growing
research today. .

The students said they
were shocked by the benefits
Eli Lilly employees receive,
including free pharmaceuti-
cal products.

area of_

company over Spring Break

Because of the company’s

size, every employee also-

has his or her own bicycle
for transportation in the
halls. Vending machines in
the company sell tickets to
sporting events, movies,
operas or plays at a discount
rate, and there are also
fitness and health centers
in every plant of the compa-

ny.

Eli Lilly provided comp1i- L

mentary limousine services
and fine cuisine, student
Jerry Simmons said.

“They were out to impress
you and did a really good
job of it,” Smith said. “It was
very different than I thought
it would be.”

Eli Lilly conducts similar
recruitment tours for 60 dif-
ferent pharmacy schools
yearly.

The experience proved to
be very educational, accord-
ing to student Jennifer
Gobrecht.

“It was a fantastic trip,” she
said.

