Study Abroad scbolarsbzps
awarded to students
travelling this summer

By Bryan N. Iams
For Tbe Pitt News

Twenty-three Pitt students will study in foreign cities ranging
from Taipei, Taiwan, to Warsaw, Poland, this summer after being
awarded Study Abroad scholarships.

The Nationality Rooms and International Exchange Programs
awarded its annual Summer Study Abroad scholarships Saturday
at the Cathedral of Learning.

Last years recipients of the award told this years awardees to
be on their guards, take advantage of the hands—on experience
and, most importantly, to soak up the whole intercultural experi-
ence.

Christie Bray, winner of this years Women’s International Club
Grant, will study in Freiburg, Germany.

‘‘I am extremely excited and hope to improve my proficiency in
the German language and become a stronger individual,” she
said.

“Studying abroad gave me a greater sense of confidence and
maturity,” said Colleen Madden, a 1992 scholarship winner. “It is
really worth it.”

These scholarships have been awarded annually to Study
Abroad students since 1948 and range from $500 to $4,000.

The scholarships, awarded to 12 graduate and 11 undergradu-
ate students, are a result of the committee’s fund raising through-
out the year. Other awards are given in memory of an individual
or by a donor who believes in the commitment of excellence that
the Study Abroad program can provide.

To be considered for a scholarship you must be a full—time Pitt
student, have between 60 and 90 credits by the end of April and
have a minimum QPA of 2.75.

If these requirements are satisfied, a student must fill out a
seven-page application and have two references by the January
deadline. '

Twenty to 25 awards are usually given to students each year.
For each award there are usually five finalists, Study Abroad pam-
phlets stated. Each finalist is given a 10-minute interview, and
then the awardee is selected by a panel of faculty members.

