Put up or shut up

In his inaugural address, Bill Clinton decreed that “There is
nothing that is wrong with America that cannot be fixed by what
is right with America.” The same holds true for the rest of the
world. The leaders of the industrialized world must hold stead-
fast to their ideological views and assure the progression of
democratic principles in the Russian republic.

On Saturday, President Boris Yeltsin sent Russia into its deep-
est crisis since the 1991 coup by declaringemergency rule and
setting a referendum on whether the people wanted him or
hard-line rulers in power.

The country has run into a frenzy. His vice president, leaders
of the parliament and the chief justice all declared Yeltsin’s
move to assume power unconstitutional. Proposals for impeach-
ment are pending.

President Clinton immediately came out in support of Yeltsin’s
decision. He said that “as Russia’s only democratically elected
national leader, he has our support as do his reform government
and all reformers throughout the Russian federation.”

But while Clinton and other Western leaders have promised to
support Russian democracy, their actions state otherwise. Thus
far, the Westhas done nothing but provide billions of dollars
worth of aid to the former republic. .

With the world’s wealthiest economies — the United States,

.Germany and Japan -—— growing slowly or not at all, and press-

ing problems in Yugoslavia, Somalia and India, foreign aid can
no longer be openly handed out. Even if it could, providing aid
does not go far enough. By the time it can be decided what to
do with the aid it is usually wasted.

The governments of the world, if they are truly dedicated to
democracy, can take several steps:

-In the case of the former Soviet Republics, Western democra-
cies must act to insure that individuals take the lead to solve the
woes facing Russia. The IMF, World Bank and G-7 nations must
guarantee foreign investment in Russia and the other Soviet
Republics. If Western firms cannot be assured of their security,
Western desires for Soviet stability will be but an empty
promise.

-Secondly, Russia has the largest oil reserves in the world. If
the West were to transfer more of its technology and know—how
to this embattled country, Russia would be much closer to a
convertible currency and thus economic stability. Most impor-
tantly, however, Russia would be learning how to cope on its
own.

-Thirdly, the West must open up its markets to Russia and
allow them to earn hard currency. Goods sold on Russian mar-
kets do not earn top prices. Open American makets during the
1950's, is one reason why the Japanese are in the position they
are now.

Economic well-being and democracy, although interrelated,
are not siblings. Institutional development and political stability
are almost as essential to the development of Russia as unfet-
tered market forces. But, at least in the short term, history has
shown us that nations can become economically prosperous
without Democratic security.

The West can claim to be supportive. But, unless they takethe
proper steps to assure Russian stability, they will be nothing
more than liars. Smaller countries like Singapore, Hong Kong
and South Korea have become major economic players because
of the liberalized American market. As did the Western
European economies after World War II.

The same kind of treatment must be given to Russia. Or, per-
haps the idea of an industrialized and wealthy Russian economy
is too much for the West to handle. If that is the case, ‘then
maybe talk of aid is for good reason.

