The bombing of the World
Trade Center occurred in a
mere momentary flash. And in
that one instant, America lost
its innocence. ‘

No longer is the United
States safe from the brutal ter-
rorist acts which have gripped
the rest of the world during
the last two decades. Seeing
thousands of innocent people
dragged out of the smoking
100—story building brought
back memories of the 1983
explosion at the Marine com-
pound in Beirut.

In the days following the
bombing, federal officials
beefed up security in major
government buildings
throughout the country.
Columnists from the New York
Times and The Washington
Post, as well as international
terrorist experts declared that
a new era has begun. The
frontier of terrorism that cur-
rently plagues Egypt, Israel,
India, the former Yugoslavia
and Great Britain has crossed
the seas onto American soil.

Some analysts say that the
United States can never
redeem its soiled image. The
ease with which the bomb
perpetrators could damage
one of America’s greatest
industrial trophies has terriﬁed
the public.

There are even some
extremists who suggest that
every public building should
become a fort like Israel,
where the threat of terrorism
has forced the government to
put up fences around public
buildings. Showing terrorists
that the United States is afraid
would only give them a major
victory in this psychological
war. ’

Instead, America needs to
regain its composure by stiff-
ening the stance against terror-

ism. Last week, Congress
introduced preventive mea-
sures against any further
attacks. '

One representative pro-
posed an anti-terrorism bill
that includes a new federal
death penalty for terrorist acts
resulting in the loss of a life,
new penalties for aiding ter-
rorists and additional proce-
dures designed to tighten up
immigration policy at U.S. air-
ports.

Another congressman sug-
gested legislation that would
bar the members of Hamas, an
Islamic fundamentalist group
now officially labeled by the
government as a group pro-
moting terrorism, from enter-
ing this country.

The Crime and Justice sub-

   
 

committee began debating
whether to expel Sheik Omar
Abdel—Rahman, the Muslim
religious leader who claimed
responsibility for terrorist acts
in Egypt and the possible mas-
termind of the New York
bombing.
I838!‘

But there is a curious ele-
ment to this latter provision.
While the connection between
the suspects at the World
Trade Center bombing and
Islamic fundamentalist groups
still remains sketchy as of this
writing, Congress has already
prepared to confront Muslim
extremists.

This legislation comes
despite the fact that FBI and
CIA officials have indefinitely
linked the bombing to the two
Palestinian suspects. There
also have not been trials or
any formal criminal proceed-

ings.

Yet, it is suspicious why
Congress has been so eager to
take a lead on this issue.
Congress surely wasn't as
enthusiastic in the early 1980s
when AIDS threatened the
security of this nation.

One explanation for this
nonincremental action is that
the United States needs a mili-
tary victory in wake of the
bloody cult compound stand-
off in Waco, Texas, and the
embattled head of the FBI
William Sessions.

There may even be a more
embedded theme here. Some
analysts say that Congress, FBI
and CIA deliberately pinned
the bombing on Muslim
extremists in order to cover up
some insidious secret from the
American public.

Examine the evidence: the
horrors Hamas and other
Islamic fundamentalist groups
committed against innocent
bystanders in Israel and Egypt
make them the perfect scape-
goat.

Who knows what kind of
evidence will turn up at the
bottom of the World Trade
Center garage in the weeks or
years to come? The investiga-
torswill hopefully nail the
right perpetrators some day.

But let’s leave that up to the
FBI and CIA.

Meanwhile, the rest of us
have lives to live, so let’s just
move on and try to return to
the waythings were. The last
things anyone should worry
about is being stranded in a
skyscraper.

Just in case though, I sure
hope Pitt’s Cathedral of

Learning building has a suffi- A

cient emergency exit system.

